blue so dark it's almost black." 
</P>
<P>
Most lobsters plucked from the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>'s icy waters are a mottled mixture of 
green, red and brown. They turn bright red when they're cooked. 
</P>
<P>
Blue lobsters are genetic mutations in which the crustacean's blue gene is 
dominant. About one in every 3 million or 4 million lobsters caught along the 
<LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> coast is blue, <PERSON>Chapman</PERSON> said. 
</P>
<P>
"Lobsters have genes for the production of red, yellow and blue," said <PERSON>Chapman</PERSON>, 
an aquaculture specialist at the <ORGANIZATION>University of Maine</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Darling Marine Center</ORGANIZATION>. 
"If the gene for red and the gene for yellow aren't functioning, you get a blue 
lobster." 
</P>
<P>
The disorder also produces lobsters with yellow shells, red shells and even 
yellow with black spots, known as calico lobsters. 
</P>
