<HEAD>Canadian Cabinet Rejects Proposed Settlement of Lobster Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian board on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> rejected a proposal to settle a
free trade dispute between lobstermen in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>.
   Canadian fishermen are allowed to keep and sell smaller lobsters
than their <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> counterparts. Representatives of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and
Canadian lobster industries recently had proposed increasing the
minimum size of lobsters taken along <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Atlantic Coast</LOCATION> to the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> level of 3\ inches.
   The proposal also called for creating a joint U.S.-Canadian
committee to discuss lobster management issues and for both
countries to work together to promote and market lobsters.
   But on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, Canadian Trade Minister <PERSON>John Crosbie</PERSON> announced
in <LOCATION>Ottawa</LOCATION> that the country's federal cabinet had rejected the
proposed settlement.
   <PERSON>John Kearney</PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>Maritime Fishermen's Union</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Yarmouth</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nova Scotia</LOCATION>, hailed the decision.
   ``We have no biological reason in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> for increasing our
minimum size,'' he said. ``We have a whole range of management and
regulatory measures ... that are non-existent in the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>.''
   But lobster industry officials from <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> predicted a worsening
of relations between the two countries because of the decision.
   ``For them to pull out of it means there's going to be more
bickering and fighting among all the various factions of the
industry,'' said <PERSON>William Anderson</PERSON>, a lobsterman from <LOCATION>Lubec</LOCATION> and
chairman of the state's <ORGANIZATION>Lobster Advisory Council</ORGANIZATION>.
   To <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> fishermen, the dispute over size is much more than
academic because they compete against Canadian lobstermen who sell
the majority of their catch in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   ``It's a big deal because so many lobsters fit into that size
range. Lobsters that are just over that (minimum) measure make up
the majority of the catch,'' said <PERSON>David Dow</PERSON>, executive director of
the <ORGANIZATION>Maine Lobster Institute</ORGANIZATION>, a scientific and educational
organization that fosters cooperation in the lobster industry.
   At the urging of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> lobstermen, President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> signed
legislation last <DATE>December</DATE> banning the import of live Canadian
lobsters that are smaller than the minimum <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> size.
   <LOCATION>Ottawa</LOCATION> contended the new law violated the U.S.-Canada Free Trade
Agreement and would cost the industry <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY> of its <MONEY>$180
million</MONEY> live lobster industry. But an international panel ruled in
late <DATE>May</DATE> that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> law did not violate the pact.
   The proposal rejected <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> called for increasing the
minimum size of lobsters taken along <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Atlantic Coast</LOCATION> to the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> level of 3\ inches from the crustacean's eye socket to the
edge of its body where the tail begins.
   Currently, <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> has a range of minimum sizes from 2{ inches to
3 3-16 inches, depending on where the lobsters are caught.
   Some Canadian lobster industry officials were upset by their
country's decision. The nation's largest lobster exporter,
<ORGANIZATION>Clearwater Fine Foods</ORGANIZATION> of suburban <LOCATION>Bedford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nova Scotia</LOCATION>, has long
supported raising size limits for what it says are conservation
reasons.
   ``There is no competent biologist who advises other than the
desirability of raising size imits,'' company spokesman <PERSON>Doug
Robinson</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>Canadian Press</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   ``The bottom line is most lobsters now caught are immature. They
have not spawned,'' he said.
</TEXT>
