<TEXT>
<P>
Mimi, the 17 1/2-pound lobster described as the <PERSON>Elizabeth Taylor</PERSON> of 
crustaceans, died of natural causes days after being shipped to her new home -- 
at a restaurant. She was between 20 and 100 years old, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Mimi, captured last week off the <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> coast and flown to <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>, died in the 
tank at <ORGANIZATION>Carl's Chop House</ORGANIZATION>, which paid <MONEY>$320</MONEY> for the huge lobster. 
</P>
<P>
"She had quit moving. I picked her up. She still didn't move," said <PERSON>Barry 
Hornecker</PERSON>, executive chef at <ORGANIZATION>Carl's</ORGANIZATION>. 
</P>
<P>
So he chilled and poached <PERSON>Mimi</PERSON> and began making plans for a feast. 
</P>
<P>
"Mimi was like <PERSON>Elizabeth Taylor</PERSON>. . . . She was always beautiful," said <PERSON>Jim 
Richards</PERSON>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION>Long Wharf Lobster Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Portland</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Me.</LOCATION>, which flew the 
lobster to <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>. 
