<LEADPARA>  Lots of live lobsters died for learning Saturday in Palo Alto.;   For more
than two hours, volunteers from the Palo Alto chapter of the American
Association of University Women traded their dressy attire for sweat shirts to
raise money for scholarships by selling shellfish.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LOBSTERS FOR LEARNING
SALE RAISES MONEY FOR WOMEN'S SCHOLARSHIPS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran without photos on page 3B of the Morning Final edition.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Eight volunteers busily handed out at least 287 live lobsters, 20 cooked
ones for the faint of heart, 85 pounds of clams and 17 dozen blue point
oysters.;   It was the group's biggest fund-raiser of the year, said <PERSON>Rosanna
Yau</PERSON>, co-chairwoman of the Lobster Sale, which has been a Palo Alto tradition
since around the mid-1970s.;   She said the <MONEY>$1,500</MONEY> raised by the sale will go
to the <ORGANIZATION>Educational Foundation</ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION>American Association of University Women</ORGANIZATION>,
which provides scholarships to women around the nation, mostly for graduate
work.;   All the shellfish were paid for in advance "so there is no risk,"
said <PERSON>Marie Walbach</PERSON>, a member.;   <PERSON>Garnet Johnson</PERSON>, co-chairman of the sale,
said, "I've been dreaming about lobsters. . . . Once in a while I have a
nightmare that the lobsters aren't coming.";   But the crustaceans arrived on
time. <PERSON>Ed Zeldin</PERSON>, a semi-retired fish wholesaler from <LOCATION>Fremont</LOCATION>, helps the <ORGANIZATION>AAUW</ORGANIZATION>
procure the seafood. The shellfish, from the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> off <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION>, were flown in live to <LOCATION>San Francisco International Airport</LOCATION>, where <PERSON>Zeldin</PERSON>
picked them up <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> in his refrigerated truck for the trip to <LOCATION>Palo
Alto.</LOCATION>;   For <ORGANIZATION>AAUW</ORGANIZATION> members, it's a time for camaraderie and friendship. <PERSON>Marcia
Baugh</PERSON>, a volunteer, said, "There is a feeling of doing something good
together. Much of what <ORGANIZATION>AAUW</ORGANIZATION> does is intellectual and this is more practical,
earthly.";   For the shoppers, it's a chance to make a contribution and have
fun later in the day. "We're going to have a party with friends," said <PERSON>Trina
Lovercheck</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION>, who heard about annual lobster parties at the sale
and decided to buy six live lobsters. "It's our first time doing it.";   <PERSON>June
Schiller</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION> watched at a slight distance while a volunteer handed
over eight of the live ones. "We have an annual party, perhaps for the past 12
years. It's a tradition. We take turns having it."  </TEXT>
