<HEAD>Bush Signs Lobster Protection Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> signed legislation <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>
banning the import of undersized lobsters.
   The bill was backed by <LOCATION>New England</LOCATION> lawmakers who presented it
both as a conservation measure and as a way to protect <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
fishermen against Canadian competitors harvesting smaller lobsters.
   The lobster provision is contained in the <MONEY>$400 million</MONEY>
authorization bill for the <ORGANIZATION>National Oceanic</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Atmospheric
Administration</ORGANIZATION>.
   Senate Majority Leader <PERSON>George Mitchell</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Maine</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Sen.
William S. Cohen</PERSON>, <LOCATION>R-Maine</LOCATION>, first sponsored the provision after
<LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> fishermen complained about Canadian competition.
   Fishermen argue that <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s smaller minimum legal size of
lobsters has allowed Canadian fishermen to catch and sell smaller,
cheaper lobsters in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> markets.
   The legislation signed by <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> would place a market representing
roughly half of <ORGANIZATION>Candada</ORGANIZATION>'s lobster exports off limits for the sale
of ``short'' lobsters.
   The current minimum legal size in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> is 3\ inches
from the eye socket to the edge of the back where the tail begins.
The Canadian minimum is one-sixteenth of an inch smaller.
   Up to now, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> law has not regulated the size of imported
lobsters.
   In coming years, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> regulations would gradually increase the
minimum size of a lobster that could be caught in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> waters.
   Because <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> would not be bound by the increased minimum size
regulation, its fishermen could continue to deplete the harvest and
compete unfairly with their <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> counterparts, lobster fishermen
argued.
</TEXT>
